---
---
<section
  data-test="problem-section"
  class="py-16 px-6 max-w-4xl mx-auto"
>
  <div class="border-t pt-16" style="border-color: var(--color-border);">
    <h2 class="font-sans text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider mb-8" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
      The Problem
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--color-text);">Spec drift</h3>
          <p class="font-serif text-base leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
            Specifications written at project start become stale. By launch, they describe a different product than what shipped.
            The drift is invisible until it's a problem, and by then it's a big one.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--color-text);">The philosophy-implementation gap</h3>
          <p class="font-serif text-base leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
            The "why" of your product lives in the founders' heads. Implementation teams work from Jira tickets.
            Somewhere between vision and pull request, coherence quietly collapses.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--color-text);">Unreliable AI output</h3>
          <p class="font-serif text-base leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
            LLMs generate plausible code that satisfies stated instructions but violates unstated intent.
            Without validation, "it compiles" is all you get. That's not good enough.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-medium mb-2" style="color: var(--color-text);">Documents nobody reads</h3>
          <p class="font-serif text-base leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-text-muted);">
            Long PRDs and design docs accumulate. Engineers guess when they can't find answers.
            Decisions get re-litigated in every sprint. The document is there; it's just wrong.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
